## Context

Social unfurl is the first impression aidemd.dev gets whenever a link leaves the site — pasted into a Slack channel, sent over iMessage, quoted in a LinkedIn post, or attached to a tweet. The unfurl is rendered by a third-party scraper (Slackbot, Twitterbot, LinkedInBot, Apple's link-preview service) that reads the page's `<head>`, fetches the image URL, and composes the preview card before anyone clicks. The audience this project is built for — founders, operators, and technical leaders evaluating whether AIDE is worth their attention — forms a trust judgment on that card alone. A missing, fragmented, or visually-off-brand unfurl costs the click, and the click is the only way the rest of the site ever gets read.

This submodule exists because the unfurl surface has two non-negotiable properties that the rest of the site does not. First, the card is rendered outside the browser by scrapers that cannot execute JavaScript, cannot hit runtime image endpoints, and cache aggressively — which forces the unfurl to be a single pre-rendered PNG on disk, not a dynamically-generated image. Second, the card's text, color, and typography must be byte-faithful to the live site, because the whole point of an unfurl is continuity: if the card promises one aesthetic and the clicked page delivers another, the trust signal breaks. Those two properties together demand a render pipeline that treats an in-repo HTML design source as the source of truth and emits one canonical PNG at build time.

Scope for v1 is deliberately one card shared across every route, not per-page variants. Per-page imagery multiplies the surface area of drift (every copy change on every route risks a stale image), it fragments the brand signal (an unfurl that looks different on every paste trains the audience that the site is inconsistent), and it offers near-zero payoff for a documentation site whose value proposition is singular. Per-page `og:title` and `og:description` overrides remain available as an additive nicety for docs routes that want to advertise their own headline, but `og:image` is locked to the one canonical asset.

## Strategy

Render the card with Playwright launched headlessly over the in-repo HTML design source, not Puppeteer or manual DevTools capture. Playwright is the CI-friendly option the handoff recommends (§3 option A), it ships a bundled Chromium that eliminates the "which Chrome version rendered this" drift problem, and its `page.locator('.og').screenshot(...)` API captures a single DOM element by selector — which is exactly the shape needed here because the design source intentionally surrounds the 1200×630 card with scaffolding (a frame-label, handoff notes, a cream-colored annotations block) that must not land in the PNG. Puppeteer can do the same job but carries no advantage; manual DevTools capture is rejected outright because it decouples the image from source-of-truth changes and is the most direct path to the stale-unfurl failure mode the frontmatter forbids.

Screenshot the `.og` element selector specifically, not `page.screenshot()` with a viewport clip. The handoff's design HTML places the card inside a wrapper that shows labels and notes for reviewer context; selector-based capture is what makes that wrapper safe to keep in the source file without leaking scaffolding into the final PNG. A viewport-clip approach would tie the output to pixel offsets that break the moment anyone adds margin around the card, whereas `page.locator('.og').screenshot(...)` resolves to the element's bounding box regardless of surrounding layout.

Keep the HTML design source inside this module as a build-time asset, never inside `public/`. The static export publishes everything under `public/` as routable URLs, and a `social-share.html` sitting at `https://aidemd.dev/social-share.html` would be a leak of design scaffolding into the shipped product — visible to anyone who guesses the URL, indexable by search engines, and an explicit violation of the frontmatter's "the design source is build-time input, not a public page" guardrail. The source lives inside `src/service/socialShare/` (alongside the orchestrator that renders from it), the render script reads it via `file://` URL, and the only artifact that reaches `public/` is the generated `og.png`.

Centralize all meta tags through Next.js App Router's `metadata` export on the root `layout.tsx`, with per-page `metadata` exports composing over it via Next's built-in merge semantics. The App Router metadata API is the static-export-safe path because it resolves to inert HTML strings at build time — no runtime, no server component re-render, no image route. A root-level `metadata.openGraph.images` entry pointing at `/og.png` guarantees every emitted page carries the canonical image; per-page overrides can supply their own `title` and `description` without touching `images`, which is how the one-canonical-card contract survives per-page personalization. Server-side OG generation (`ImageResponse`, `@vercel/og`, the `app/opengraph-image.tsx` convention) is disqualified because it requires a Node runtime at request time, which the root intent's static-export contract forbids.

Run the render script as a `prebuild` step so `og.png` is produced on every build and can never go stale against the shipped HTML. The frontmatter lists "rendered card drifting from the design source" as an undesired outcome, and the only durable defense is making regeneration automatic rather than optional. A `prebuild` hook ties the image's freshness to the same command that ships the site (`npm run build`), which means the static export cannot be produced without a current `og.png`. Manual render-on-content-change is rejected because it depends on a human remembering, which is the category of failure the "hard gate" undesired outcomes exist to prevent.

Wait for `networkidle` before capture, and self-host the JetBrains Mono font file rather than relying on Google Fonts at render time. The handoff's design HTML loads the font via `fonts.googleapis.com`; leaving that in place makes the build pipeline depend on a third-party CDN being reachable from wherever the render runs, and a silent font-load failure swaps in a fallback whose glyph metrics shift the 64px headline's line breaks and the caret's vertical alignment. Self-hosting the weight set (400 / 500 / 600 / 700) the card actually uses eliminates the network dependency entirely and makes the capture deterministic; the `networkidle` wait is kept as a belt-and-suspenders guard for any remaining async work (the `expo-wave.png` image decode in particular).

Constrain the card to the site's warm-dark tokens exactly: `#0d0b08` bg, `#16120d` card surface, `#e8dfce` fg, `#3d6b4a` forest-green accent, with dimmed text at `rgba(232,223,206,0.55)` and `rgba(232,223,206,0.35)`. These are the same values the site's live terminal uses, and visual continuity between unfurl and destination is what converts the click. The accent in particular is a common drift point — material-design green, tailwind's `green-600`, or any "close enough" hex replacement fragments the brand signal and is called out in the undesired outcomes. Reading these values from the same token source the site uses (rather than hard-coding them in the design HTML) would be better, but for v1 the tokens are duplicated into `social-share.html` and kept in sync by convention; if the site's token file changes, the design source must be updated in the same commit.

Hold the PNG under 300 KB with appropriate compression. 300 KB is the hard ceiling because Twitter/X silently falls back from `summary_large_image` to the small summary card when the image exceeds its budget, and summary-small is indistinguishable from "unfurl broke" for the audience. Playwright's default PNG output is typically well under the ceiling for a 1200×630 card with this palette (dark backgrounds compress well), but the build script should verify the byte size after capture and fail the build if it exceeds 300 KB rather than shipping a degraded card.

Write `og:image:alt` as exactly "Expo, the AIDEMD mascot, waving next to the tagline 'intent is the source.'" and treat the mascot's name as a first-class correctness concern. The root intent forbids the abandoned "Aidey"/"AID" names from appearing anywhere in shipped output; alt text is shipped output, even though it is invisible to sighted users, because screen readers speak it and crawlers index it. The alt string, the source asset filename (`expo-wave.png`), and any HTML comments in the design source must all say Expo.

## Good examples

**A correctly-rendered unfurl pasted into Slack.** The card renders at the large-image size with the warm-dark `#0d0b08` background and a faint dotted grid. A 46px-tall terminal chrome bar runs across the top: three window-dots (red, yellow, green), then the prompt `$ aidemd.dev/intent-is-the-source` with the `$` in forest green, then right-aligned meta reading `LIVE` (with a glowing green dot before it) and `v0.1.0`. Below the chrome, the left column carries the tag line `## canonical docs · the .aide methodology` with the `##` in forest green, the 64px headline `intent is` followed on a new line by `the source.` in forest green with a blinking-caret block after the period, the subhead about byte-faithful timestamped records, and three chips reading `scope: narrowed`, `outcomes: declared`, `brain: obsidian` each with a 2px forest-green left border. The right column shows Expo the mascot waving at roughly 500px tall, with a terminal-styled speech bubble above her shoulder that reads `EXPO SAYS: the .aide is the contract — read the docs to see why.` Registration corner marks in forest green sit at the four corners of the card. Title under the card reads `AIDEMD.DEV — intent is the source`, description reads `A byte-faithful record of the .aide methodology. Every .aide is a contract — scope, outcomes, guardrails — that cascades through your stack.`

**A correct `og:image:alt` string.** `Expo, the AIDEMD mascot, waving next to the tagline 'intent is the source.'`

**A correct per-page override.** The docs page at `/docs/aide-spec` emits its own `og:title` of `aide-spec.md — AIDEMD.DEV` and its own `og:description` of `The canonical schema for .aide files: scope, intent, outcomes.desired, outcomes.undesired.` The `og:image`, `og:image:width`, `og:image:height`, `og:image:alt`, and `twitter:card` values are inherited unchanged from the root layout — the unfurl shows the same Expo card with the docs page's headline in the title slot.

**A correct Twitter Card Validator response.** The validator fetches `https://aidemd.dev/` and reports: card type `summary_large_image`; image URL `https://aidemd.dev/og.png` resolved, 1200×630, sRGB, 187 KB; title `AIDEMD.DEV — intent is the source`; description `A byte-faithful record of the .aide methodology.`; preview panel shows the Expo card filling the full horizontal width of the tweet frame.

## Bad examples

**A stale unfurl.** The marketing site's headline has been changed to `intent is the contract.` and deployed, but the `prebuild` render step was skipped or silently failed and the old `og.png` (reading `intent is the source.`) is still on disk. Slack fetches the stale image and shows an unfurl whose headline does not match the page the user clicks through to. The audience reads this as "the site is out of date" — the exact opposite of what an authoritative methodology home is supposed to signal.

**A per-page `og:image` fragmenting the brand.** The `/docs/outcomes` page defines its own `opengraph-image.tsx` that renders a variant card with a different headline. Every docs route now has a slightly-different unfurl — some have Expo, some don't, some carry the tagline, some carry a schema diagram. The audience sees three different AIDEMD.DEV cards in three different Slack channels over the course of a week and concludes the site is inconsistently maintained. The one-canonical-card contract in the frontmatter is broken.

**A naked URL with no card at all.** A route under `/docs/agents/researcher` is emitted without the root layout's metadata attached (a copy-paste page skeleton that overrode `metadata` to an empty object instead of extending the root). Pasting the link into iMessage shows the raw URL text with no image, no title, no description — indistinguishable from a broken link. The unfurl contract fails for that entire subtree of the site.

**An off-palette card.** A designer regenerates the card after a well-meaning edit to the design HTML that swapped the `#3d6b4a` accent for `#4caf50` (Material Design's green), because it "looked more vibrant in the Figma mock." The accent now appears on the prompt sigil, the `##` tag, the caret, the chip borders, and the registration marks — bright saturated green against the warm-dark palette. The unfurl still renders, but the color cast is wrong enough that the landing page's actual `#3d6b4a` accent reads as a downgrade when the user clicks through. Visual continuity is broken.

**An alt string that re-leaks the abandoned name.** `og:image:alt` is written as `Aidey, the AIDEMD mascot, waving next to the tagline 'intent is the source.'` Sighted users never see this, so the error ships unnoticed — but screen readers announce "Aidey" to the audience most likely to care about accessibility details, and search crawlers index the abandoned name against the site. The root intent's prohibition on the abandoned names in shipped output is violated silently.

